First note that \(B\) and \(E\) are both \(2\times2\) matrices, so \(B - E\) is defined.  Compute entry‐wise:

\(B - E = \begin{pmatrix}2&14\\22&6\end{pmatrix} \;-\;\begin{pmatrix}6&12\\14&5\end{pmatrix}
=\begin{pmatrix}2-6&\,14-12\\22-14&\,6-5\end{pmatrix}
=\begin{pmatrix}-4&2\\8&1\end{pmatrix}.\)

First note that \(B\) is \(2\times2\), so \(B^2=B\cdot B\) is defined.  Compute:

\[
B^2
=\begin{pmatrix}40&10\\-20&30\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}40&10\\-20&30\end{pmatrix}
=\begin{pmatrix}
40\cdot40+10\cdot(-20) & 40\cdot10+10\cdot30\\
-20\cdot40+30\cdot(-20) & -20\cdot10+30\cdot30
\end{pmatrix}
=\begin{pmatrix}
1600-200 & 400+300\\
-800-600 & -200+900
\end{pmatrix}
=\begin{pmatrix}
1400 & 700\\
-1400 & 700
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

To compute \(B^2 = B\cdot B\), note that \(B\) is the permutation matrix that swaps the 2nd and 3rd basis vectors.  Applying it twice returns each vector to itself, so you get the identity.  In coordinates,

\[
B^2 \;=\;
\begin{pmatrix}
1&0&0\\
0&0&1\\
0&1&0
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
1&0&0\\
0&0&1\\
0&1&0
\end{pmatrix}
\;=\;
\begin{pmatrix}
1&0&0\\
0&1&0\\
0&0&1
\end{pmatrix}.
\]
